[start section id="20112"]

Reviewed outside colonoscopy and pathology reports, CT report.  His film is on QREADS, and his slides have been read by Pathology.
#1 Metachronous colon cancer in the setting of left-sided colitis
Mr. Benefield presents to O'Connor Hospital of Brooklyn for treatment of colon cancer.  This is his second colorectal cancer as he is status-post low-anterior resection in 1999 for T3, N0, M0 rectal cancer.  He has left-sided colitis diagnosed two years ago, currently off any treatment.  He suffers from five to ten loose stools daily with associated fecal incontinence.  I shared with him that it maybe reasonable to consider a total colectomy or subtotal colectomy potentially with a stoma instead of a segmental resection.  As reviewed with Dr. Weaver, we will repeat a colonoscopy and obtain further biopsies to assess the extent of the colitis.  Liver ultrasound will also be checked, and his outside CT will be sent to Radiology for interpretation.  Lab work, chest x-ray, and ECG are pending.  Patient will meet with Dr. Grassi from Colon and Rectal Surgery upon completion of his evaluation for surgical discussion.  He may need to meet with the stoma nurse if the surgeon recommends a stoma.
#2 Preoperative medical evaluation
Lab work, chest x-ray, and ECG are pending.  Once these are obtained and satisfactory, the patient is okay for anesthesia.  I will obtain baseline amylase and lipase levels given his history of pancreatitis, although this currently appears stable.  Please see HPI for significant comorbidities of renal insufficiency, history of pancreatitis, and diabetes mellitus.
I discussed with Dr. Lindsay Weaver.  Note to follow.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: Yes, on file at Uncas on Thames Medical Clinic.

